@SaintPeter:
> `git reset --hard upstream <master branch>`

That doesn't seem to work, don't you mean `git reset --hard @{u}`?

@theflametrooper BTW, if you find your self in such a bind that you think you need re-fork your repo, here is a magic wand that will fix all:
`git reset --hard upstream <master branch>`
That effectively discards any local changes to the current branch and resets it to the `upstream` head (along with all associated history).  This should save you from having to delete and refork.
